You need 120 units to graduate. NP units will not count toward this total, so if you need more than 4 units to get to 120 you can't NP those classes. You also can't graduate with more than 1/3 of your units as P/NP, so if taking all 3 of those classes P/NP will push you above 1/3 you also will have to opt to take some for a letter grade. Otherwise, I think that should be fine since you're passing your breadth requirement.

I'm a last semester senior and I have stayed an extra semester mostly for learning's sake. I have already completed all of the required CS upper-divs and pre-reqs. All I have left is the International Studies breadth.

ECON 175 - (International Studies breadth) - 4 units

CS 189 - (for interest) - 4 units

CS 184 - (for interest) - 4 units

Suppose that I were to receive the following grades:

ECON 175 = P

CS 189 = NP

CS 184 = NP

What would happen? Are there secret L&S or CS department rules that would mean that disqualifies me from graduating?

Obviously I don't plan to NP any classes, but I'm curious and it would help me to know that the "worst-case scenario" isn't that bad.
history.subject: One requirement left. Can I P/NP All My Classes and Still Graduate?
